Pictured: Mentawais Moonscape by Randall Jones

"In retrospect women recognize they made more mistakes related to the dissolution of their partnerships than they perceived at the time. For many, the steps leading to the final separation greatly contribute to this retrospective view," says ffm project director Christa Mattos. She explains that a key factor that weakened and broke up a partnership after the arrival of a child was a lack of commitment. This was followed by infidelity, changes of residence and a cemented routine once they were no longer happy. There was also a significant proportion of women who claimed they lacked the courage to openly communicate their unhappiness. The ffm study also reveals that, afterwards, women who crept away felt "the ghost of guilt" nevertheless haunted them.

Russian immigrants: Like-minded compatriots ensure survival

Pictured: German indie-rock musician Clara Luzia from Graz (Austria)

Rumour has it that it's particularly difficult to form a marital partnership with an African. However, in everyday life Africans go out of their way to avoid contact with each other. Many strive to identify themselves as representatives of Swiss culture and struggle to integrate themselves into Swiss society. The integration of the Russian middle class is reportedly significantly more successful: Refugees from the Soviet Union have a culture and language in common with their Swiss colleagues, and may understand each other even if they speak different dialects
